Right! In fact I believe the above code invokes undefined behavior, because b may be accessed for a reason other than to determine its new value, without an intervening sequence point.<p>Put another way, the compiler can arbitrarily interleave the subexpressions within separate arguments:<p><pre><code>    foo( a() && b(), c() && d() );
</code></pre>
The compiler is free to invoke these functions in the order a(), c(), d(), b() if it pleases.
